  "response": "In J.R.R. Tolkien's works, the Necromancer is actually Sauron in disguise, before he fully reveals himself as the Dark Lord of Mordor. In \"The Hobbit,\" he is initially referred to only as the Necromancer of Dol Guldur, a dark sorcerer dwelling in a fortress in Mirkwood. Though he doesn't appear directly in the main narrative, he is a significant background threat. Gandalf investigates him and ultimately helps drive him out of Dol Guldur, which is later revealed to be a preliminary step in Sauron's return to power. In Tolkien's broader mythology, this period represents Sauron's early attempts to regain strength after his defeat in the War of the Last Alliance.",
